Good work, boss.

35:16.215 --> 35:17.349
Nice work, Walter.

35:17.383 --> 35:18.584
Nice work, Walter.
[CLEARS THROAT]

35:19.185 --> 35:20.686
Thank you, boys.

35:20.719 --> 35:21.720
I'll have a bowl.

35:24.256 --> 35:25.224
Same.

35:27.359 --> 35:28.460
Same.

35:28.494 --> 35:29.395
Same.

35:29.928 --> 35:30.829
Same.

35:31.397 --> 35:32.564
Okay.

35:32.598 --> 35:33.632
[EXPLOSION AND CLATTERING]

36:23.849 --> 36:24.916
[VEHICLE APPROACHING]

36:29.455 --> 36:30.356
Damn it.

36:31.657 --> 36:32.691
It's only dirt.

36:33.525 --> 36:34.793
Afternoon, boys.

36:34.826 --> 36:35.794
ALL: Good afternoon, Father.

36:39.365 --> 36:40.232
Walter.

36:42.434 --> 36:43.269
HARLAN: Your wife, Patricia.

36:49.040 --> 36:49.875
[BELLS JANGLING]

36:51.343 --> 36:52.210
HARLAN: Henry.

36:54.446 --> 36:55.347
Irwin's still sick.

36:57.316 --> 36:58.917
I'm sorry, Father.

36:58.950 --> 36:59.785
MAN: [ON RADIO] ...would like
me to relay

36:59.818 --> 37:01.287
a message to all...

37:01.320 --> 37:04.456
Well, you got anything
that'll keep his spirits up
and his fever down?

37:05.957 --> 37:07.759
If I was those parents,
I'd be ashamed.

37:08.894 --> 37:11.963
Well, most parents
can't see their child ill.

37:12.898 --> 37:13.965
So they throw him in a lake.

37:14.700 --> 37:16.302
[CLICKS TONGUE]

37:16.335 --> 37:17.769
It all depends, Henry,
on how you look at it.

37:18.904 --> 37:20.839
Either you're halfway to
heaven or halfway to hell.

37:23.342 --> 37:24.242
Here we go, Father.

37:24.843 --> 37:25.944
It's an antibiotic.

37:27.846 --> 37:29.481
Inject five cc's
of this into his arm.

37:30.382 --> 37:31.082
All right?

37:32.551 --> 37:34.420
Bless you.
Have a safe journey.

37:34.453 --> 37:35.354
Thank you, Father.

37:36.388 --> 37:37.756
MAN: [ON RADIO]
We thank you in advance,

37:37.789 --> 37:39.725
and hope you have
a pleasant journey.
[BELLS JANGLING]

38:07.953 --> 38:08.920
[MUSIC BOX PLAYING]

39:09.548 --> 39:10.549
Pop?

39:10.582 --> 39:11.583
Yeah, son?

39:14.152 --> 39:15.621
You suppose he's got two
of everything in there?

39:17.723 --> 39:18.557
WALTER: I suppose
we'll find out.

39:21.860 --> 39:23.429
* Now I don't care

39:24.563 --> 39:26.698
* If I'm not the first

39:26.732 --> 39:27.633
Damn it.

39:29.635 --> 39:30.602
I know.

39:33.004 --> 39:35.874
WALTER: Not one,
but two Chevys.

39:39.177 --> 39:40.111
I know.

39:43.081 --> 39:44.015
This is gonna be difficult.

39:47.753 --> 39:48.854
Yep. [SIGHS]

39:51.590 --> 39:53.425
Ever since we started
moving folks out,

39:56.127 --> 39:58.063
we've never done well with
people that owned Chevrolets.

40:00.866 --> 40:01.967
Matt.

40:05.136 --> 40:08.974
This country is being divided
into two types of people.

40:11.743 --> 40:12.678
Chevy people.

40:16.848 --> 40:17.983
And Ford people, Matt.

40:20.886 --> 40:21.987
Yep.

40:24.590 --> 40:25.491
[COUNTRY MUSIC PLAYING]

40:29.761 --> 40:33.231
* Now, I don't care

40:33.264 --> 40:36.935
* If I'm not the first love
you've known

40:38.103 --> 40:41.206
* Just so I'll be the last

40:43.809 --> 40:45.544
* Now, I don't care

40:46.912 --> 40:48.179
[METAL CLANGING]

40:48.213 --> 40:50.048
Looks like he's got
some kind of a hammer.

40:54.786 --> 40:57.689
No, it looks more like a...

40:57.723 --> 40:58.924
[GUN FIRING]
[GLASS SHATTERING]

41:04.062 --> 41:05.196
I think
he was holding a shotgun.

41:06.064 --> 41:07.198
[GUN COCKING]

41:08.066 --> 41:08.967
WALTER: I think you're right.

41:17.943 --> 41:19.077
[GUNSHOT]

41:20.746 --> 41:21.613
[GUN FIRING IN THE DISTANCE]

41:22.781 --> 41:24.049
Every town we come to,

41:25.150 --> 41:26.184
you want a child.

41:27.819 --> 41:29.120
Once again, selfish.

41:30.756 --> 41:31.723
How observant.

41:32.624 --> 41:33.725
The noble Englishman.

41:35.093 --> 41:36.962
How I longed to be Earl Gray.

41:38.830 --> 41:39.965
The wit that got us here.

41:41.700 --> 41:42.534
It's a splendid acquisition.

41:43.735 --> 41:44.636
Unknown architect.

41:46.204 --> 41:47.238
Probably owner-builder.

41:48.907 --> 41:50.208
HAPPY: A true visionary,
I might add.

41:50.241 --> 41:51.142
Jesus.

41:52.177 --> 41:54.112
No, no, he was a carpenter.

41:56.081 --> 41:57.248
We, we're searching
for the unknown.

41:59.250 --> 42:01.553
The unknown doesn't just
come knocking on your door.

42:03.321 --> 42:06.658
If it is unknown,
how would you know if
it did come knocking?

42:08.093 --> 42:09.561
Well, it won't be
in the shape of a child.

42:10.896 --> 42:12.197
I would have to agree.
FLOWER: Happy?

42:14.933 --> 42:16.001
Do you ever disagree?

42:18.336 --> 42:20.606
[CHUCKLES] I disagree with the
Englishman's use of starch.

42:23.642 --> 42:24.610
What do the scriptures say?

42:29.948 --> 42:32.283
"Temperature,
105 degrees. High.

42:33.619 --> 42:36.021
"Please look after him
when I leave."

42:36.855 --> 42:37.723
[MUSIC BOX PLAYING]

42:46.898 --> 42:47.766
[MUSIC STOPS]

42:50.902 --> 42:51.737
What do you suppose we do?

42:53.271 --> 42:54.272
We're gonna wing it.

42:56.307 --> 42:57.242
[CREAKING]

43:11.957 --> 43:12.791
[GUNSHOTS]
[METAL CLANKING]

43:41.019 --> 43:41.887
[BELL RINGING]

43:47.358 --> 43:48.359
MARVIN: It appears they've...

43:49.961 --> 43:50.762
Worn out their welcome.

44:00.338 --> 44:01.472
Good afternoon, Mr. Stalling.

44:01.506 --> 44:04.109
My name is Walter O'Brien.
This here's my son, Willis.

44:04.142 --> 44:05.711
We're with
the evacuation committee.

44:05.744 --> 44:07.012
It's been brought
to the state's attention

44:07.045 --> 44:07.645
that you are seeking
some assistance.

44:09.047 --> 44:11.416
I'm not going anywhere, son.

44:11.449 --> 44:14.319
We're aware of that, sir,
that's why the state has
asked us to come to your aid.

44:14.352 --> 44:16.321
The state understands your
difficulty with moving on.

44:16.354 --> 44:19.124
GROUP: "The state
will not hurt, destroy,

44:20.158 --> 44:23.695
"nor harm you physically
in any way.

44:23.729 --> 44:29.200
"It is our civil duty to
assist you in
making this transition

44:29.234 --> 44:32.137
"as easy and pleasant
as possible."

44:40.946 --> 44:41.813
Your agreement is this,

44:43.882 --> 44:46.752
you will each be assigned
65 households to depart.

44:48.754 --> 44:50.255
Having fulfilled
said obligation,

44:51.857 --> 44:54.692
you will then
each receive 1.5 acres

44:56.094 --> 44:57.428
of prime, lakefront property.

44:59.430 --> 45:00.465
Your lot size
will be increased

45:01.632 --> 45:04.269
by one-fifth of an acre
for every additional household

45:04.302 --> 45:06.437
that you assist in evacuating
beyond the initial 65.

45:09.074 --> 45:09.908
Have I made myself clear?

45:17.048 --> 45:18.216
I will take
your vacant stares as a yes.

45:23.054 --> 45:24.222
[PANTING] I could live
with an acre and a half.

45:25.891 --> 45:26.925
[GUNSHOT]

45:28.093 --> 45:28.994
Okay by me.

45:33.298 --> 45:34.332
May we, sir?

45:54.920 --> 45:55.887
So.

45:58.957 --> 45:59.891
The prodigal son returns.

46:01.860 --> 46:02.493
Already packed.

46:03.261 --> 46:04.362
A little ahead of yourself.

46:05.964 --> 46:06.898
I've brought
what you're looking for.

46:08.133 --> 46:09.034
You have?

46:10.969 --> 46:11.837
Outside.

46:19.110 --> 46:19.945
I don't see anything.

46:21.012 --> 46:22.480
We still have a deal?
CUP OF TEA: Yes, yes, yes.

46:22.513 --> 46:23.414
We have a deal.

46:26.117 --> 46:27.385
Yeah, we still have a deal.

46:30.188 --> 46:31.256
Where is it?

46:38.263 --> 46:39.397
Oh, my.

46:42.567 --> 46:43.501
[CREAKING]

46:56.948 --> 46:57.883
Hello.

46:58.984 --> 46:59.550
[MUFFLED MUSIC PLAYING]

47:19.404 --> 47:20.438
[MUSIC PLAYING CLEARLY]

47:28.179 --> 47:29.180
We'd appreciate it

47:29.214 --> 47:31.149
if you both would

47:31.182 --> 47:32.083
stop screwing around.

47:41.659 --> 47:43.461
Well, what do you
want to do?

47:43.494 --> 47:44.595
The Youngs are going
to have a moving sale.

47:47.132 --> 47:48.066
Perfect.

47:50.368 --> 47:51.469
[CHIRPING]

47:53.604 --> 47:55.573
STALLING: Now,
all I need is a pair
of sinners like yourselves

47:55.606 --> 47:57.442
to mount up there now.

47:57.475 --> 47:59.044
We appreciate very much
your giving us this time

47:59.077 --> 48:00.045
to discuss this matter.

48:02.647 --> 48:04.049
[WHISPERING] A pair of wives?

48:04.082 --> 48:04.615
At least they're not mounted.

48:05.550 --> 48:06.584
You know, it appears to me
that you folks

48:06.617 --> 48:09.520
are preparing for a flood
in biblical proportions.

48:09.554 --> 48:11.056
You got that right, son.

48:11.089 --> 48:12.490
A flood is gonna wipe
through this place,

48:13.491 --> 48:14.592
cleansing the soil of all sin.

48:15.226 --> 48:16.995
Understandable.

48:17.028 --> 48:18.529
When God tells us
to get a move on,

48:18.563 --> 48:20.031
we're gone at the first holler
of a rooster.

48:21.366 --> 48:22.934
We ain't needing the state
to come in here,

48:22.968 --> 48:23.935
and tell us when
to pick up and get going.

48:25.036 --> 48:25.770
That's God's doing.

48:27.005 --> 48:30.475
This is God's land,
and by God,

48:30.508 --> 48:32.643
we ain't moving until we get
that sign from above.

48:35.346 --> 48:37.148
Yes, sir. Uh...

48:37.182 --> 48:38.549
We aren't telling you
to pick up and get going.

48:38.984 --> 48:40.318
No, sir.

48:40.351 --> 48:41.619
Look at us
as your life preservers.

48:41.652 --> 48:42.653
You can use us if you want,

48:43.188 --> 48:44.122
or not at all.

48:44.655 --> 48:46.324
We give you that choice.

48:46.357 --> 48:48.093
We're all in the same boat.
[CHUCKLES]

48:48.126 --> 48:49.560
So, sir,
if you don't mind, sir,

48:49.594 --> 48:52.964
I'd like to bend you
and your wives' ear a bit,

48:52.998 --> 48:54.165
and tell you about
the signs of God

48:55.333 --> 48:56.534
that we are familiar with.

49:03.008 --> 49:04.409
This could be that sign.
[DEEP RUMBLE]

49:06.411 --> 49:07.478
A what?

49:08.513 --> 49:09.547
He said he was a relative.

49:10.281 --> 49:11.182
To us?

49:15.253 --> 49:16.187
Yes.

49:17.455 --> 49:18.656
You're the unknown angel?

49:19.424 --> 49:21.192
Yes.

49:21.226 --> 49:23.461
The one you're looking for.
CUP OF TEA: Optimistic.

49:24.762 --> 49:25.696
He is unknown.

49:26.564 --> 49:27.665
The angel part's questionable.

49:28.266 --> 49:29.200
Very.

49:40.578 --> 49:41.579
CUP OF TEA: How romantic.

49:43.281 --> 49:44.049
There's a novel
about you, too.

49:51.589 --> 49:52.623
I started to collect these.

50:01.399 --> 50:03.034
This is the first one I grew.

50:05.070 --> 50:06.537
WALTER: Now I'm not saying
that this boat

50:06.571 --> 50:07.672
you have built
isn't worthy.

50:08.473 --> 50:10.141
From the looks of it,

50:10.175 --> 50:11.142
you've done a mighty fine job.

50:12.443 --> 50:15.012
But for the sake of my job,
let's just say

50:16.214 --> 50:17.082
it doesn't.

50:18.216 --> 50:19.084
Doesn't what?

50:21.152 --> 50:22.253
Your boat doesn't float.

50:22.287 --> 50:24.222
Imagine this, if you will.
One day,

50:25.490 --> 50:26.724
a town on the plains,
let's say Northfork,

50:27.758 --> 50:29.160
was hit by
a catastrophic flood,

50:30.595 --> 50:31.629
similar to the days of Noah,

50:32.497 --> 50:33.731
and your husband
and yourselves

50:33.764 --> 50:36.033
are standing out there
on the roof waiting
to be rescued.

50:37.435 --> 50:39.737
A friendly neighbor
comes paddling by
in his little wooden boat,

50:41.172 --> 50:42.773
and he yells, "Hey, there,
Mr. and Mrs. Stalling,

50:42.807 --> 50:44.775
"and... Uh, Mrs. Stalling,
jump on in,

50:45.876 --> 50:47.112
"and I'll take you
to dry land."

50:48.546 --> 50:49.714
What do you say?

50:50.348 --> 50:51.282
I don't know.

50:52.150 --> 50:54.152
The water's rising.
You shout back,

50:54.185 --> 50:56.121
"No, thank you,
thy friendly neighbor.

50:56.154 --> 50:58.256
"I'm waiting
for a sign from God."

50:59.290 --> 51:00.625
No, thank you.

51:00.658 --> 51:04.095
I'm waiting for a sign
from God.

51:04.129 --> 51:07.365
Yes, exactly.
And your friendly neighbor
paddles away.

51:07.398 --> 51:08.266
[WATER SLOSHING]

51:10.635 --> 51:12.737
WALTER: A few days later,

51:12.770 --> 51:16.073
a state rescue team
comes by in a larger boat.

51:17.575 --> 51:18.543
And let's just say...
[CHURCH BELLS]

51:19.410 --> 51:21.679
...me and Willis are on board.

51:22.580 --> 51:24.682
And we offer you
the same deal.

51:26.284 --> 51:27.785
"Jump on in,

51:27.818 --> 51:31.722
"and you, Mrs. Stalling
and... Mrs. Stalling,

51:32.523 --> 51:33.558
"will be saved."

51:35.860 --> 51:37.128
And you say,

51:38.729 --> 51:40.531
"No, thank you.

51:40.565 --> 51:41.766
"We're waiting
for a sign from God."

51:44.569 --> 51:45.836
WALTER: A few more days pass,

51:47.305 --> 51:49.240
and the water level has risen.

51:50.708 --> 51:53.144
It has risen above the roof.
[BUBBLING]

51:54.245 --> 51:55.180
And unfortunately,

51:56.013 --> 51:58.283
you and Mr. Stalling
have drowned,

52:00.851 --> 52:03.354
and now are in heaven
in front of God.

52:06.424 --> 52:07.725
Dear, we died.

52:08.859 --> 52:09.894
What about our belongings?

52:11.329 --> 52:12.263
[GLASS SHATTERING]

52:15.333 --> 52:16.334
[CLATTERING]

52:24.609 --> 52:25.710
MRS. STERLING: We died?

52:25.743 --> 52:26.911
Oh, yes, you three
have died,

52:26.944 --> 52:29.180
because you waited
for a sign from God,

52:29.214 --> 52:31.148
and it never came,
and you three died.

52:31.882 --> 52:32.850
But why?

52:34.885 --> 52:36.321
That's the exact question
you would ask God.

52:39.224 --> 52:43.160
You would say, "We waited for
the sign and it never came."

52:44.629 --> 52:46.897
And you and she,

52:49.767 --> 52:50.868
and Mr. Stalling

52:53.538 --> 52:54.639
died.

52:56.707 --> 52:57.908
Now what do you suppose

52:59.944 --> 53:00.911
God

53:03.781 --> 53:05.216
is gonna say to you both?

53:06.684 --> 53:07.785
I don't know.

53:10.621 --> 53:11.689
Mr. Stalling?

53:12.890 --> 53:14.225
I'm dead, remember?

53:15.460 --> 53:16.461
May I?
Yes.

53:17.562 --> 53:18.729
I'll tell you
what God will say.

53:19.597 --> 53:21.299
"I sent you two boats."

53:21.332 --> 53:22.533
"Two boats."

53:22.567 --> 53:23.668
"To save your lives."

53:25.803 --> 53:28.439
"What more of a sign
did you three want?"

53:30.475 --> 53:31.309
[SIGHS]
[DEEP RUMBLE]

53:32.543 --> 53:33.711
May I?

53:35.280 --> 53:36.647
Fascinating.

53:36.681 --> 53:37.648
FLOWER: You have a lovely

53:37.682 --> 53:38.849
collection of feathers.

53:39.584 --> 53:40.718
Thank you.

53:41.686 --> 53:42.720
And your halo.

53:46.691 --> 53:47.725
Where's that?

53:52.597 --> 53:53.898
[WHISPERING]
They took it off
when I was little.

53:53.931 --> 53:54.965
I didn't need it anymore.

53:57.868 --> 53:58.969
And these must be your wings.

54:18.055 --> 54:18.923
Oh, mighty.

54:20.425 --> 54:21.326
Look at this.

54:23.861 --> 54:25.463
And where did we get this?

54:27.097 --> 54:28.833
MRS. STALLING:
These are quite stunning.

54:29.900 --> 54:31.436
The grace of God.

54:31.469 --> 54:32.837
WILLIS: Yes, they are.

54:32.870 --> 54:34.805
We're offering you
a pair of something that
only the man upstairs

54:34.839 --> 54:35.873
is willing to give you.

54:36.874 --> 54:38.876
Where'd you get these boys?

54:38.909 --> 54:40.345
Born and raised
right here in Northfork.

54:41.479 --> 54:42.480
Dear, what are you thinking?

54:43.781 --> 54:46.584
I'm thinking,
what bird suffered this?

54:46.617 --> 54:48.052
Oh, there's nothing
fowl about these wings.

54:48.085 --> 54:49.887
I understand
your initial doubt,

54:49.920 --> 54:51.422
but how many times
have you seen wings

54:52.623 --> 54:53.491
of this size and beauty?

54:56.827 --> 54:57.995
IRWIN: This is what

54:58.028 --> 54:59.063
most of us were shot with.

55:00.765 --> 55:01.899
Tranquility at its finest.

55:03.768 --> 55:04.869
This could make
an elephant fly.

55:05.803 --> 55:07.071
IRWIN: It stuck in me

55:07.104 --> 55:07.972
right here.

55:14.812 --> 55:15.713
May I look?

55:17.815 --> 55:19.850
Appears to be lengthy
needle of some sort.

55:21.386 --> 55:22.520
HAPPY: Five years,
maybe six years of age.

55:23.688 --> 55:25.456
Used numerous times
for injection.

55:27.792 --> 55:28.859
You were shot with this rifle?

55:29.560 --> 55:31.095
Yes.

55:31.128 --> 55:33.063
I was running with my flock
and they shot me.

55:34.765 --> 55:35.800
You were running
with your flock?

55:36.701 --> 55:37.968
Yes.

55:38.002 --> 55:39.604
CUP OF TEA: Flock of what?

55:39.637 --> 55:42.507
Doves? Geese?
Seagulls?

55:43.541 --> 55:44.442
Angels.

55:46.944 --> 55:48.879
MR. STALLING:
Angel wings, huh?

55:48.913 --> 55:50.515
I'm here to tell you
these wings is worthless.

55:51.048 --> 55:52.983
And to remove all doubt,

55:53.017 --> 55:54.385
we included this certificate
of authenticity.

55:55.520 --> 55:59.890
Signed, sealed and blessed
by your own Father Harlan.

56:01.559 --> 56:02.927
"Found near the glaciers,

56:02.960 --> 56:04.562
"these wings,
blah, blah, blah."

56:04.595 --> 56:06.831
"From what they could tell,
this particular pair were
detached from a juvenile

56:07.832 --> 56:08.833
"who probably strayed
from the flock.

56:10.735 --> 56:12.603
"Perhaps no wiser
than four years of age.

56:14.104 --> 56:15.840
"The abbreviated
wingspan reveals to us

56:17.508 --> 56:19.109
"that he weighed no more
than 25 to 30 pounds

56:21.579 --> 56:22.580
"before they were removed."

56:25.115 --> 56:26.383
A bit too disturbing for me.

56:29.954 --> 56:30.988
FLOWER: Happy.

56:32.757 --> 56:33.524
Are you looking at this?

56:34.725 --> 56:35.860
[RUMBLING]
[GLASS CLINKING]

56:43.634 --> 56:44.602
Would you say amputated?

56:45.803 --> 56:47.538
Yes. Amputated.

56:48.739 --> 56:50.007
HAPPY: Fascinating.

56:50.040 --> 56:51.108
CUP OF TEA:
Angel. [SCOFFS]

56:52.242 --> 56:53.143
Aren't we all?

56:53.911 --> 56:54.879
I'd say quite the opposite.

56:55.980 --> 56:56.781
Probably a little devil,

56:58.148 --> 56:59.016
and daddy gave him
a good strapping.

57:00.017 --> 57:01.018
There's a backstory for you.

57:03.020 --> 57:04.555
Does this cause any pain?

57:05.189 --> 57:06.123
No.

57:07.625 --> 57:08.559
This would be recognized

57:10.160 --> 57:12.463
as a highly dangerous
procedure without anesthesia.

57:12.997 --> 57:14.164
Some people would just

57:14.932 --> 57:16.033
bite a bullet.

57:17.635 --> 57:19.003
A highly

57:19.036 --> 57:22.773
skilled surgeon
was overly concerned

57:22.807 --> 57:23.941
with muscle stabilization.

57:28.713 --> 57:30.214
There's no evidence of
curvature of the spine.

57:35.620 --> 57:39.490
You're discovering
feathers in this area?

57:40.190 --> 57:41.125
Yes.

57:42.593 --> 57:43.561
What time of day?

57:43.928 --> 57:45.095
IRWIN: Morning.

57:46.296 --> 57:47.932
Can you run your fingers
through his hair?

57:56.073 --> 57:57.241
What can you tell us
about your relatives?

57:59.143 --> 58:02.980
My mother and father were
12th generation angels.

58:03.013 --> 58:06.651
My great grandpa and grandma
had wings the size

58:06.684 --> 58:08.919
of bombers and would
glide the plains

58:08.953 --> 58:10.087
of Northfork.

58:12.823 --> 58:13.624
MR. STALLING: Come on,
you ladies,

58:13.658 --> 58:15.092
can't you just smell
the bird shit?

58:17.227 --> 58:19.063
I mean, I'd like to believe
these wings is authentic,

58:19.096 --> 58:20.064
but the feathers,

58:21.098 --> 58:22.032
they ain't attached
to anything.

58:24.569 --> 58:25.736
You take those moose antlers
back there.

58:27.004 --> 58:28.539
Oh, dear.

58:28.573 --> 58:29.774
Yeah, it's a fine

58:29.807 --> 58:30.675
set of antlers,

58:31.609 --> 58:33.043
but it's more
than just a rack of horns

58:33.844 --> 58:34.712
attached to a piece of board.

58:36.681 --> 58:37.281
That wouldn't be enough.

58:38.649 --> 58:39.717
It's an okay place
to hang your hat,

58:41.952 --> 58:42.720
but there ain't
no pride in it.

58:45.022 --> 58:47.558
What you need is the whole
head hanging up there.

58:49.293 --> 58:51.696
And these marble eyes just
staring on down at you.

58:54.632 --> 58:56.533
Then you know you've got
something really worth having.

58:58.235 --> 58:59.203
MR. YOUNG:
We're still not leaving.

59:04.775 --> 59:05.976
[CLATTERING]

59:06.010 --> 59:08.245
I've got a $1,000
check from the state,

59:08.278 --> 59:10.047
or would you rather use that
for your funeral services?

59:12.282 --> 59:13.317
No.

59:13.350 --> 59:15.319
Then you best get the hell
out of here right now.

59:20.090 --> 59:21.191
Use these to fly
the hell out of here.

59:24.862 --> 59:25.796
Wow.

59:29.634 --> 59:30.300
[SNORING]

59:55.425 --> 59:56.661
[WHISPERING]
Eddie. Hey, Eddie.

59:58.929 --> 01:00:00.064
I think Jigger's asleep.

01:00:20.184 --> 01:00:21.218
Let's go.

01:01:01.859 --> 01:01:02.793
[SNORING]

01:01:15.005 --> 01:01:16.273
ARNOLD: Jesus Christ.

01:01:44.034 --> 01:01:45.202
HAPPY: The scars on
his forehead

01:01:46.236 --> 01:01:47.437
tell me he did have a halo.

01:01:49.073 --> 01:01:50.407
Most likely metal.

01:01:50.440 --> 01:01:51.842
To stabilize his...
[RIFLE FIRING]

01:01:52.442 --> 01:01:53.778
Oh.

01:01:53.811 --> 01:01:54.478
Everything all right?

01:01:56.080 --> 01:01:58.749
Dankish, beetle-headed
foot-licker.

01:02:00.050 --> 01:02:00.985
FLOWER: What is wrong
with you?

01:02:05.856 --> 01:02:06.791
Happy?

01:02:08.225 --> 01:02:09.726
You should be asking yourself
that question.

01:02:11.929 --> 01:02:12.930
Fired from
a long barrel rifle.

01:02:13.798 --> 01:02:14.731
Ten feet away.

01:02:15.900 --> 01:02:18.803
Needle meant to penetrate
two to three inches of skin.

01:02:19.569 --> 01:02:20.971
Perhaps the hide
of a herbivore.

01:02:22.472 --> 01:02:24.474
Beast to the hallucinogenic.

01:02:26.576 --> 01:02:28.178
Would you like
a cup of tea?

01:02:28.212 --> 01:02:29.246
This isn't tea time.

01:02:30.047 --> 01:02:30.848
Given my weight,

01:02:32.850 --> 01:02:33.818
calculated dosage,

01:02:35.953 --> 01:02:37.354
this could be a lengthy trip.

01:02:38.889 --> 01:02:39.857
Moist.

01:02:40.557 --> 01:02:41.491
Mother.

01:02:42.827 --> 01:02:43.760
May I?

01:02:44.128 --> 01:02:45.262
No.

01:02:45.830 --> 01:02:46.763
Yes.

01:02:48.866 --> 01:02:49.967
CUP OF TEA: Plenty more
where that came from.

01:02:51.568 --> 01:02:52.469
Here.

01:02:55.239 --> 01:02:56.506
Shoot me, shoot Cod.

01:02:57.341 --> 01:02:58.508
And then shoot yourself
in the foot.

01:02:58.976 --> 01:03:01.045
No.

01:03:01.078 --> 01:03:04.815
You saucy, sheep-biting
flat-mouthed dewberry.
This could be a family...

01:03:04.849 --> 01:03:06.050
[RIFLE FIRING]
[GLASS BREAKING]

01:03:07.918 --> 01:03:08.785
[THUDDING]

01:03:11.922 --> 01:03:12.823
Oh.

01:03:19.329 --> 01:03:20.397
HAPPY: Santa's everywhere.

01:03:23.033 --> 01:03:24.001
I'm Happy.

01:03:25.135 --> 01:03:26.036
[THUDDING]

01:03:39.884 --> 01:03:41.551
This should back off
some evil spirits.

01:03:42.987 --> 01:03:43.921
Hmm?

01:03:44.889 --> 01:03:45.589
Oh.

01:03:46.957 --> 01:03:47.892
Hmm.

01:03:50.227 --> 01:03:51.061
[QUIET SIGH]

01:04:06.410 --> 01:04:07.444
[TRUNK CLOSING]

01:04:12.449 --> 01:04:13.884
Two out of three
ain't that bad.

01:04:13.918 --> 01:04:15.519
Damn it.
I say we hook that thing up

01:04:15.552 --> 01:04:16.620
to our bumper
and drag it out ourselves.

01:04:18.322 --> 01:04:19.556
What are you talking
about, Willis?

01:04:19.589 --> 01:04:20.424
WILLIS: You know why?
I'll tell you why.

01:04:20.457 --> 01:04:22.159
That there was number 65.

01:04:22.192 --> 01:04:24.028
I know that, Willis.

01:04:24.061 --> 01:04:25.595
I'm marking them
down as departed.
We can't.

01:04:27.664 --> 01:04:28.966
The state makes
their final pass-through,

01:04:30.467 --> 01:04:32.169
and they find that
Mr. Stalling locked up in that

01:04:32.202 --> 01:04:33.037
boat with his

01:04:33.570 --> 01:04:34.504
moose head.

01:04:35.239 --> 01:04:36.941
It's our butt.

01:04:36.974 --> 01:04:38.976
It's our job
to move them out of Northfork.

01:04:39.009 --> 01:04:40.945
It's not our job
to know where they go.

01:04:40.978 --> 01:04:42.412
Willis, it's our job

01:04:42.446 --> 01:04:43.513
to move people,

01:04:45.149 --> 01:04:46.316
not change their beliefs.

01:04:46.350 --> 01:04:47.384
WILLIS: What more

01:04:47.417 --> 01:04:48.485
could we have said?

01:04:51.121 --> 01:04:51.989
Without the proper words,

01:04:53.323 --> 01:04:54.358
this is just a man,

01:04:55.359 --> 01:04:56.360
nailed to two pieces of wood.

01:05:01.165 --> 01:05:02.099
[WHISPERING] Oh, he's cute.

01:05:03.968 --> 01:05:04.935
IRWIN: Father?

01:05:09.373 --> 01:05:11.241
[WHISPERING] Yes, son.

01:05:11.275 --> 01:05:12.376
[WHISPERING] I don't think
they want me.

01:05:13.110 --> 01:05:14.144
Oh, no, they do.

01:05:15.179 --> 01:05:16.613
They do, son.

01:05:16.646 --> 01:05:18.182
They came a long way for you.

01:05:19.549 --> 01:05:20.650
Then, can I go with them?

01:05:24.688 --> 01:05:26.423
I will still have to speak
with them.

01:05:27.992 --> 01:05:29.493
Then, can you tell them
I'm an angel?

01:05:33.563 --> 01:05:35.665
I will. I will.

01:05:37.067 --> 01:05:38.668
Because I want them
to see my wings.

01:05:40.470 --> 01:05:41.571
Do you have wings?

01:05:43.540 --> 01:05:44.941
Yeah? Me too.

01:05:45.509 --> 01:05:47.211
But mine got old and fell off.

01:05:48.645 --> 01:05:50.080
You get some sleep now.

01:05:51.215 --> 01:05:52.416
All right.

01:05:59.256 --> 01:06:00.490
HARLAN: Mr. And Mrs. Hope?

01:06:01.258 --> 01:06:02.426
Yes.

01:06:02.459 --> 01:06:03.560
I'm Father Harlan.

01:06:04.494 --> 01:06:05.996
Father.

01:06:06.030 --> 01:06:07.464
Thank you for coming
on short notice.

01:06:09.133 --> 01:06:10.634
Irwin is a good boy.

01:06:13.170 --> 01:06:15.139
I could go on,

01:06:15.172 --> 01:06:17.741
but that would seem
like I'm selling him to you.

01:06:19.443 --> 01:06:20.510
And I'm not.

01:06:21.445 --> 01:06:23.013
What? You're not...

01:06:23.047 --> 01:06:25.382
Well, given the chance,
I'm sure Irwin

01:06:25.415 --> 01:06:27.684
would do a better job
at selling himself...

01:06:27.717 --> 01:06:29.119
Oh.
[CHUCKLES SOFTLY] Than me.

01:06:30.054 --> 01:06:30.720
Can we meet him?

01:06:34.091 --> 01:06:34.824
Unfortunately,

01:06:35.659 --> 01:06:36.726
you will have
to make a decision

01:06:37.694 --> 01:06:38.728
before you can meet him.

01:06:40.830 --> 01:06:42.432
But, Father,
it says right here

01:06:42.466 --> 01:06:44.234
that we can spend
the afternoon with him.

01:06:45.102 --> 01:06:46.270
Yes, I know. I...

01:06:46.303 --> 01:06:47.637
I'm sorry. I apologize.

01:06:48.705 --> 01:06:50.507
But Irwin is a fragile boy.

01:06:52.509 --> 01:06:55.279
I can't let him
get his hopes up too high,

01:06:55.312 --> 01:06:56.746
only to have them diminished.

01:06:58.548 --> 01:07:01.751
His health can't afford
that kind of a disappointment.

01:07:04.154 --> 01:07:05.722
Oh, Father,
we can't make a decision

01:07:05.755 --> 01:07:07.491
based upon viewing
him from a window.

01:07:11.228 --> 01:07:12.229
I'm sorry.

01:07:18.702 --> 01:07:19.769
[WHISPERING] Why don't you go
wait in the car?

01:07:20.504 --> 01:07:21.638
[SOBBING]

01:07:27.677 --> 01:07:29.279
[CAR DOOR CLOSING]

01:07:29.313 --> 01:07:31.548
Father, we come here
attempting to adopt a child,

01:07:32.649 --> 01:07:34.084
and you turn it
into window shopping.

01:07:35.519 --> 01:07:36.553
He's not a puppy.

01:07:37.454 --> 01:07:38.522
Oh.

01:07:40.524 --> 01:07:43.527
Well, maybe that's what
you and your wife
should be considering.

01:07:46.263 --> 01:07:47.431
I'm sorry

01:07:47.464 --> 01:07:49.166
if I have wasted your time.

01:07:51.268 --> 01:07:52.202
Have a pleasant journey.

01:08:00.444 --> 01:08:02.146
[STATIC]

01:08:02.179 --> 01:08:04.614
RADIO ANNOUNCER: Many
townspeople have speculated

01:08:04.648 --> 01:08:07.217
that the body of Jimmy Miller,

01:08:07.251 --> 01:08:08.752
son of Doris and James Miller,

01:08:09.653 --> 01:08:11.155
still lays in
the Northfork dam.

01:08:11.755 --> 01:08:13.857
One worker has said,

01:08:13.890 --> 01:08:16.693
"There is a slight lump
in the interior wall

01:08:16.725 --> 01:08:20.163
"that will hold back
19 million acres of water."

01:08:20.197 --> 01:08:22.832
Another worker said,
"Yes, Jimmy is in there.

01:08:23.867 --> 01:08:25.301
"They never could retrieve him
from the dam.

01:08:26.303 --> 01:08:29.139
"He is resting in peace."

01:08:29.173 --> 01:08:31.608
Tom Johnson, a fisherman,
put it this way,

01:08:32.776 --> 01:08:35.779
"Heck, you can't exactly
troll 100 feet

01:08:35.812 --> 01:08:38.648
"of just-poured concrete
fishing for a body."

01:08:38.682 --> 01:08:39.683
WALTER: Marvin. Matt.

01:08:40.649 --> 01:08:42.618
MARVIN: Walter. Willis.

01:08:42.652 --> 01:08:47.157
Tours of the Northfork dam,
and possibly Jimmy Miller,
will be starting in January.

01:08:47.657 --> 01:08:49.559
For more information,

01:08:49.593 --> 01:08:51.694
please contact Montana's
water and power.
[STATIC]

01:08:53.497 --> 01:08:54.363
Somebody is laying there.

01:08:57.767 --> 01:08:58.801
You feel a heartbeat?

01:09:00.270 --> 01:09:01.171
No.

01:09:02.572 --> 01:09:03.673
You can figure...

01:09:05.309 --> 01:09:06.843
A death of a person is
still considered progress.

01:09:10.680 --> 01:09:12.749
Son of a bitch is getting
the biggest headstone

01:09:12.782 --> 01:09:13.817
this side of Rushmore.

01:09:24.394 --> 01:09:25.662
Yeah.

01:09:25.694 --> 01:09:27.397
Congratulations.

01:09:27.430 --> 01:09:28.665
Sixty-five residents departed.

01:09:29.533 --> 01:09:30.399
Good job.

01:09:31.368 --> 01:09:32.902
You sign on that bottom line,

01:09:32.935 --> 01:09:35.372
1.5 acres will be transferred
into your name.

01:09:53.390 --> 01:09:54.991
Hmm.

01:09:55.024 --> 01:09:59.396
Well, your log reads
64 residents departed.
Is this correct?

01:10:00.430 --> 01:10:01.398
Well, sir...
Yes, sir, it is.

01:10:03.867 --> 01:10:05.802
[SIGHS] Well, you know what?

01:10:07.771 --> 01:10:09.806
I'd like to thank you
personally for your hard work
and dedication

01:10:09.839 --> 01:10:11.875
in the evacuation
of Northfork,

01:10:11.908 --> 01:10:12.976
and hope to see you boys
out there enjoying the lake.

01:10:14.344 --> 01:10:15.245
Wait a minute. That's it?

01:10:15.845 --> 01:10:16.846
We get nothing?

01:10:18.748 --> 01:10:19.849
That's correct.

01:10:21.285 --> 01:10:22.218
Sir, there...

01:10:24.588 --> 01:10:26.823
There is another house
that we did not confirm
their departure.

01:10:28.425 --> 01:10:29.759
Well, then, you best
go out there and
get it confirmed, huh?

01:10:45.709 --> 01:10:46.810
Duck.

01:10:55.719 --> 01:10:56.820
Duck.

01:11:05.962 --> 01:11:06.863
Goose.

01:11:07.731 --> 01:11:09.366
Boy was a tad pigeon-toed.

01:11:12.769 --> 01:11:13.837
What do you think?

01:11:14.838 --> 01:11:16.873
For most, Vincent van Gogh
was a fine artist.

01:11:17.674 --> 01:11:18.975
To some, he lacked technique.

01:11:20.209 --> 01:11:22.312
HAPPY: Paint straight
from the tube,
very heavy-handed.

01:11:36.593 --> 01:11:37.861
How van Gogh cut off his ear

01:11:38.995 --> 01:11:40.430
is what is most intriguing
to folks.

01:11:41.665 --> 01:11:43.700
In each piece
I've ever appraised,

01:11:43.733 --> 01:11:46.436
the story is always
more fascinating than
the actual piece itself.

01:11:48.505 --> 01:11:49.473
And?

01:11:51.040 --> 01:11:53.477
It's a fantastic yarn
the boy has spun.

01:11:53.510 --> 01:11:54.378
Unfortunately,

01:11:56.380 --> 01:12:00.049
the story is more valuable
than the actual piece.

01:12:03.787 --> 01:12:05.088
What about his collection
of feathers?

01:12:07.023 --> 01:12:09.058
Perhaps from the stork
that dropped him.

01:12:10.894 --> 01:12:11.961
Feathers are inconsistent.

01:12:13.663 --> 01:12:15.932
HAPPY: I couldn't find any
connection in the scriptures.

01:12:15.965 --> 01:12:17.100
CUP OF TEA: And that spleeny

01:12:17.801 --> 01:12:18.835
ill-nurtured gnat.

01:12:20.670 --> 01:12:22.372
FLOWER: Are you positive?

01:12:22.406 --> 01:12:25.375
Oh, Flower, please,
be open to inconsistency.

01:12:27.043 --> 01:12:28.445
Where did the feathers
come in?

01:12:30.414 --> 01:12:31.381
A book.

01:12:32.549 --> 01:12:34.418
The book was in a pillowcase.

01:12:34.451 --> 01:12:35.919
I presume that the pillow
that the boy

01:12:35.952 --> 01:12:37.454
lays his head on
is stuffed with feathers.

01:12:40.156 --> 01:12:41.825
He is not
what we are here for.

01:12:43.860 --> 01:12:45.629
La Fleur was touched
by an angel.

01:12:48.465 --> 01:12:49.399
[SQUEAKING]

01:13:01.745 --> 01:13:02.579
[WATER SPLASHING]

01:13:10.887 --> 01:13:12.055
Is it snowing?

01:13:25.469 --> 01:13:26.436
[EXHALES]

01:13:28.472 --> 01:13:29.473
Can I go?

01:13:40.750 --> 01:13:42.619
* You're not mine anymore

01:13:43.487 --> 01:13:44.153
This is it, son.

01:13:47.891 --> 01:13:48.892
Looks pretty vacant.

01:13:49.959 --> 01:13:51.561
* To say you've
changed your mind *

01:13:51.595 --> 01:13:52.462
Indeed it does.

01:13:54.731 --> 01:13:56.500
* I know you remember

01:14:09.112 --> 01:14:11.180
* If you don't ever
change your mind *

01:14:32.669 --> 01:14:33.537
Trick or treat.

01:14:34.103 --> 01:14:35.104
[PLUCKING NOTE]

01:14:50.086 --> 01:14:51.120
[DOOR CREAKING]

01:15:13.943 --> 01:15:14.978
Smells like something
died in here.

01:15:16.112 --> 01:15:18.214
That is precisely why
we're not going to get Mother.

01:15:22.118 --> 01:15:23.987
Willis, you smell that?

01:15:24.020 --> 01:15:25.088
Yeah, it smells
like something died.

01:15:39.936 --> 01:15:41.571
Go upstairs and check
all the rooms.
Then we'll leave.

01:15:47.310 --> 01:15:48.277
What?

01:15:49.713 --> 01:15:51.247
You're kidding.

01:15:51.280 --> 01:15:52.782
You go upstairs
and check
everything out.

01:15:52.816 --> 01:15:55.318
Willis, go upstairs,
and see if anyone is up there.

01:15:59.155 --> 01:16:00.590
I'm personally not ready
to face death.

01:16:01.925 --> 01:16:02.826
This is number 65.

01:16:03.893 --> 01:16:06.029
Go upstairs, check it out,

01:16:07.196 --> 01:16:08.164
and let's get this over with.

01:16:09.999 --> 01:16:10.767
I'm checking out
the other side.

01:16:11.935 --> 01:16:12.802
Willis.

01:16:14.638 --> 01:16:15.739
Willis!

01:16:15.772 --> 01:16:16.640
[SNORING CUTS OFF]

01:16:44.868 --> 01:16:45.869
Hello?

01:17:02.118 --> 01:17:03.119
Hello there.

01:17:21.137 --> 01:17:22.238
[WIND WHOOSHING]

01:17:27.977 --> 01:17:28.912
Pop.

01:17:31.715 --> 01:17:32.381
WILLIS: Pop!

01:17:35.885 --> 01:17:36.786
[WIND WHOOSHING]

01:17:42.225 --> 01:17:43.259
Do you see anything?

01:17:45.494 --> 01:17:46.395
No.

01:17:48.965 --> 01:17:50.266
Come on. Jump.

01:17:52.268 --> 01:17:53.269
It's about five feet, come on.

01:17:54.804 --> 01:17:55.705
You can make it. Jump.

01:17:58.842 --> 01:17:59.776
Come on.

01:18:01.310 --> 01:18:02.311
Pop, come on, jump!

01:18:04.147 --> 01:18:04.948
You can make it. Come on.

01:18:12.121 --> 01:18:13.156
[THUDDING]

01:18:13.990 --> 01:18:14.924
[CRASHING]

01:18:17.894 --> 01:18:19.028
[GROANS]

01:18:19.062 --> 01:18:19.896
FLOWER: Are you okay?

01:18:21.464 --> 01:18:22.866
Would you like a cup of tea?

01:18:25.101 --> 01:18:26.135
HAPPY: I would qualify this

01:18:26.169 --> 01:18:27.370
in the area of concussion.

01:18:29.005 --> 01:18:31.374
A frothy, clay-brained
snapper.

01:18:31.407 --> 01:18:32.742
Let's help you get up
onto your feet.

01:18:38.848 --> 01:18:39.816
Definitely gonna
feel that in the morning.

01:18:44.387 --> 01:18:45.454
Willis, let's go.

01:18:46.089 --> 01:18:47.123
Did you see anyone?

01:18:47.156 --> 01:18:48.257
Nope.

01:18:51.194 --> 01:18:52.228
Come on!

01:18:54.063 --> 01:18:54.964
Come on!

01:18:56.565 --> 01:18:57.433
Get in the car!

01:18:59.468 --> 01:19:00.403
Get!

01:19:01.938 --> 01:19:02.906
What's got you so spooked?

01:19:04.273 --> 01:19:06.242
* If you don't ever
change your mind

01:19:07.343 --> 01:19:08.978
* To take me back again
Grab the book.

01:19:09.012 --> 01:19:10.113
Pop...

01:19:10.146 --> 01:19:11.014
Just do it!

01:19:11.915 --> 01:19:13.149
[ENGINE STARTING]

01:19:13.182 --> 01:19:14.250
Mark them down as evacs.

01:19:14.984 --> 01:19:15.885
"Evacuated."

01:19:17.220 --> 01:19:18.287
Do it!
Okay, I will.

01:19:19.322 --> 01:19:22.091
* Since the day you say
we're through

01:19:22.125 --> 01:19:26.329
* I'm even more
in love with you

01:19:26.362 --> 01:19:27.897
* And it's my fault that
you're not mine anymore

01:19:28.965 --> 01:19:29.999
And I think we should
go get your mom.

01:19:55.859 --> 01:19:56.525
Hmm...

01:19:58.594 --> 01:20:00.496
HAPPY: These have
the same texture

01:20:00.529 --> 01:20:01.530
as the feathers that were
in the boy's book.

01:20:09.538 --> 01:20:10.506
Mmm-hmm.

01:20:12.241 --> 01:20:13.342
Mmm-hmm.

01:20:15.111 --> 01:20:16.479
No more than
four years of age.

01:20:18.314 --> 01:20:19.515
Weighed no more
than 30 pounds.

01:20:22.418 --> 01:20:24.087
These were attached
to something very young.

01:20:26.189 --> 01:20:27.523
I'm going to have
to evaluate the other side.

01:20:30.226 --> 01:20:31.094
Fascinating.

01:20:34.330 --> 01:20:35.331
HARLAN: Oh, lord.

01:20:36.432 --> 01:20:37.967
Let the holy angels come

01:20:38.334 --> 01:20:39.435
to Irwin,

01:20:41.337 --> 01:20:43.572
and carry him
to your heavenly city.

01:20:48.111 --> 01:20:49.078
Free his spirit

01:20:52.148 --> 01:20:54.017
from the prison of his body.

01:21:21.010 --> 01:21:21.945
[MUMBLING]

01:21:27.250 --> 01:21:28.151
[TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

01:21:52.675 --> 01:21:53.542
Fascinating.

01:21:56.379 --> 01:21:57.480
No.

01:21:59.115 --> 01:22:00.483
[SOBBING] Please, no.

01:22:01.650 --> 01:22:02.518
[SIGHING]

01:22:06.755 --> 01:22:07.690
Oh.

01:23:11.820 --> 01:23:13.022
HARLAN: I'm a man of faith.

01:23:17.360 --> 01:23:19.028
Forgiveness is my job.

01:23:24.300 --> 01:23:25.201
But right now,

01:23:28.304 --> 01:23:29.738
I can't forgive my faith.

01:23:35.844 --> 01:23:36.779
Hmm.

01:23:41.450 --> 01:23:42.551
Here.

01:23:44.853 --> 01:23:47.090
He grew two inches
this summer.

01:24:12.681 --> 01:24:13.782
[WALTER SNIFFLING]

01:24:18.587 --> 01:24:20.656
Pop.
[WALTER SNIFFLING]

01:24:21.524 --> 01:24:22.558
Still stacking wood?

01:24:25.894 --> 01:24:26.829
Yep.

01:24:40.443 --> 01:24:41.310
WILLIS: Pop?

01:24:47.216 --> 01:24:48.151
Yeah?

01:24:50.153 --> 01:24:51.554
You're not even close
to what death smells like.

01:25:22.318 --> 01:25:23.219
I'm sorry.

01:25:28.757 --> 01:25:29.892
I'm coming to get you.

01:25:32.695 --> 01:25:34.129
I'm sorry.

01:25:41.437 --> 01:25:42.871
I didn't forget you.

01:25:51.947 --> 01:25:53.216
I'm sorry.

01:25:59.322 --> 01:26:00.389
I'm sorry.

01:26:04.427 --> 01:26:05.394
[SNIFFLES]

01:26:12.568 --> 01:26:13.869
[BRAKES SQUEALING]

01:26:13.902 --> 01:26:14.770
WILLIS: Pop.

01:26:15.504 --> 01:26:16.405
Come here.

01:26:17.640 --> 01:26:18.607
[CAR DOOR CLOSING]

01:26:18.641 --> 01:26:19.675
What?

01:26:24.580 --> 01:26:25.414
Can you see?

01:26:26.449 --> 01:26:27.383
What?

01:26:28.451 --> 01:26:30.353
Look closer.

01:26:30.386 --> 01:26:31.387
No, I can't see anything.
What am I looking for?

01:26:32.521 --> 01:26:33.489
There's a nick in my paint.

01:26:33.522 --> 01:26:34.457
There's a nick in my paint!

01:26:36.425 --> 01:26:37.426
[GRUNTS]

01:26:38.794 --> 01:26:40.496
Don't make it worse.

01:26:40.529 --> 01:26:42.931
Don't make it worse.
It's only dirt.
I was rubbing it off.

01:26:42.965 --> 01:26:45.000
What color is dirt?
Brown?

01:26:45.033 --> 01:26:46.669
If Marvin weren't blind,
he would see that

01:26:46.702 --> 01:26:48.904
it was gray,
the color underneath my paint.

01:26:48.937 --> 01:26:50.306
WALTER: Willis,
the speck is brown.

01:26:50.339 --> 01:26:51.274
Look.

01:26:53.376 --> 01:26:55.544
Brown after Marvin's
filthy hands rubbed it!

01:26:55.578 --> 01:26:57.613
Well, I can't see
how you'd think you could keep
your car perfect

01:26:57.646 --> 01:26:58.414
the way you drive anyway.

01:26:59.348 --> 01:27:00.416
It hurts.

01:27:00.449 --> 01:27:01.717
The first one hurts.

01:27:03.018 --> 01:27:04.553
You just never know
when it's gonna come.

01:27:04.587 --> 01:27:05.421
You know, that's fate for you.

01:27:07.290 --> 01:27:08.223
A little rock.

01:27:10.726 --> 01:27:11.694
You do not have a say
in the matter.

01:27:19.702 --> 01:27:20.736
Now that you've gotten
the first one,

01:27:24.573 --> 01:27:25.441
the rest comes easy.

01:27:27.676 --> 01:27:28.944
You spend all your time

01:27:30.546 --> 01:27:31.280
polishing your car,

01:27:32.715 --> 01:27:33.982
making everything
look perfect.

01:27:35.451 --> 01:27:36.419
Then this rock

01:27:37.386 --> 01:27:38.321
flies out of nowhere,

01:27:39.655 --> 01:27:40.856
and puts all your
hard work to shame.

01:27:49.865 --> 01:27:50.899
Nothing you can do, though.

01:27:56.672 --> 01:27:57.740
Absolutely nothing.

01:28:02.611 --> 01:28:03.512
[CAR EXHAUST BANGS]

01:28:04.347 --> 01:28:05.314
[VEHICLE APPROACHING]

01:28:07.483 --> 01:28:08.884
Holy cow.
Oh, my God.

01:28:25.901 --> 01:28:26.935
[CAR PARTS CLANGING]

01:28:29.372 --> 01:28:30.439
[DEEP RUMBLING]

01:29:02.938 --> 01:29:06.709
[WALTER MUMBLING
THROUGH HANDKERCHIEF]

01:29:06.742 --> 01:29:07.910
Into the hole.
Take that.

01:29:09.077 --> 01:29:11.514
So when you get down in there,

01:29:11.547 --> 01:29:13.382
you just thread this rope
through the top handle.

01:29:15.784 --> 01:29:16.885
What?

01:29:17.953 --> 01:29:18.987
You jump down there and do it.

01:29:20.122 --> 01:29:22.124
WALTER: Willis.
WILLIS: No more.
No, no, no, no.

01:29:22.157 --> 01:29:23.091
This is downright
wrong.

01:29:24.660 --> 01:29:26.094
Once something's buried,
it should stay buried.

01:29:26.962 --> 01:29:27.930
I can't show no more respect.

01:29:32.000 --> 01:29:33.669
WALTER: You know,
when this small town

01:29:33.702 --> 01:29:36.505
becomes the biggest lake
this side of the Mississippi,

01:29:36.539 --> 01:29:38.674
your mother will be
the catch of the day!

01:29:38.707 --> 01:29:40.643
Then throw some rocks on her.
That should keep her down.

01:29:48.884 --> 01:29:49.852
MARVIN: Where are you
gonna take her?

01:29:52.120 --> 01:29:53.155
EDDIE: What about California?

01:29:55.524 --> 01:29:56.391
MATT: What's there?

01:29:57.593 --> 01:29:59.094
ARNOLD: I heard in California

01:29:59.127 --> 01:30:01.964
they're serving cheeseburgers
and a soda in less than
two minutes flat.

01:30:02.798 --> 01:30:04.433
MARVIN: Wow.

01:30:04.467 --> 01:30:05.133
That's fast food.

01:30:19.982 --> 01:30:22.017
I know you've been praying.

01:30:24.687 --> 01:30:25.621
Not to worry.

01:30:27.590 --> 01:30:28.657
A family will come soon.

01:30:37.666 --> 01:30:38.901
You may be an orphan,

01:30:43.205 --> 01:30:45.040
but you're still
a child of God.

01:30:49.545 --> 01:30:50.713
HAPPY: We must go
get him, Flower.

01:30:52.881 --> 01:30:54.149
FLOWER: If I didn't
know your voice,

01:30:54.182 --> 01:30:55.684
I would think it
was my subconscious.

01:30:58.186 --> 01:30:59.187
[SNIFFLES]

01:30:59.988 --> 01:31:01.089
Could he be?

01:31:05.060 --> 01:31:06.061
HAPPY: He is.

01:31:08.931 --> 01:31:09.765
[SIGHS]

01:31:13.235 --> 01:31:14.603
You don't want to
believe him, do you?

01:31:15.904 --> 01:31:17.172
[SOBS]

01:31:17.205 --> 01:31:18.073
You do?

01:31:18.807 --> 01:31:19.942
[SIGHS]

01:31:26.849 --> 01:31:28.116
He's just a child.

01:31:29.885 --> 01:31:30.953
I can't accept that.

01:31:31.954 --> 01:31:33.021
[SIGHS]
Yes, I know.

01:31:34.657 --> 01:31:35.558
We can't.

01:31:36.959 --> 01:31:38.026
We have to.

01:31:40.095 --> 01:31:41.597
You have to.
[SIGHS]

01:31:44.633 --> 01:31:46.535
Don't let your motherly nature
cost you your manhood.

01:31:49.838 --> 01:31:50.739
He prayed for us.

01:31:53.075 --> 01:31:54.109
[BREATHES DEEPLY]

01:32:24.106 --> 01:32:26.041
WALTER: 1.5 acres
of lakefront property.

01:32:27.275 --> 01:32:28.210
Hmm.

01:32:28.911 --> 01:32:30.012
MARVIN: Northern pike?

01:32:30.879 --> 01:32:31.747
Might be.

01:32:32.781 --> 01:32:33.849
EDDIE: Pike's not a fish,

01:32:33.882 --> 01:32:34.817
it's a dog.

01:32:35.884 --> 01:32:36.785
Skull full of teeth.

01:32:38.153 --> 01:32:39.722
Pick those suckers up
by their eye sockets.

01:32:40.956 --> 01:32:41.857
Weapons of
massive destruction.

01:32:43.759 --> 01:32:46.762
They drop that Pike's milt
into this lake.

01:32:46.795 --> 01:32:48.731
WILLIS: You can forget
all about the fish living in
peace and harmony.

01:32:50.165 --> 01:32:51.166
Pike eat their children.

01:32:53.201 --> 01:32:55.671
What they should do
is introduce a nice game fish
like the muskie.

01:32:56.839 --> 01:32:58.874
Now, that's a fine species.
Hmm.

01:32:58.907 --> 01:33:01.677
No fish from Minnesota
should be allowed to
swim past the Missouri.

01:33:03.345 --> 01:33:05.080
If the fine citizens
of Northfork knew

01:33:05.113 --> 01:33:06.181
that muskie was swimming
through their houses,

01:33:07.816 --> 01:33:09.885
we would've never been able to
get 'em to leave.

01:33:09.918 --> 01:33:12.788
Canada ought to claim that
bug-heap they call Minnesota.

01:33:14.189 --> 01:33:15.323
Throw in Wisconsin for free.

01:33:25.100 --> 01:33:27.069
You have to think
that this must have been
his last day on the job.

01:34:04.139 --> 01:34:05.273
[ENGINE STARTS]

01:34:45.447 --> 01:34:46.414
You ready?

01:34:47.750 --> 01:34:48.851
One thousand miles?

01:34:51.186 --> 01:34:52.387
Farther.

01:34:53.221 --> 01:34:54.356
You're a relative.

01:35:01.930 --> 01:35:02.765
[CHUCKLES] Hercules.

01:35:04.366 --> 01:35:05.901
The strongest man
ever to wear a skirt.

01:35:08.536 --> 01:35:10.806
Are you going to be my mother
or my father?

01:35:12.875 --> 01:35:13.809
I'm both.

01:35:16.912 --> 01:35:18.180
Considered the perfect soul,

01:35:20.048 --> 01:35:22.217
I search for no one,
and no one looks for me.

01:35:23.986 --> 01:35:25.921
Whatever I need I look
within myself to find.

01:35:27.322 --> 01:35:28.390
I am complete.

01:35:29.291 --> 01:35:31.827
I am not king nor queen,
yet I am both.

01:35:33.361 --> 01:35:34.462
A mother and a father.

01:35:36.198 --> 01:35:38.233
You prayed to be this way?

01:35:40.168 --> 01:35:42.004
Isn't that
what Father Harlan says?

01:35:42.037 --> 01:35:42.971
"Pray and you shall receive"?

01:36:19.274 --> 01:36:20.342
Would you like a cup of tea?

01:36:20.976 --> 01:36:21.844
[LAUGHS]

01:37:01.249 --> 01:37:02.317
[LAUGHING]

01:37:20.535 --> 01:37:21.569
Irwin?

01:37:24.039 --> 01:37:25.007
Well?

01:37:41.156 --> 01:37:42.324
There you go, son.

01:37:43.225 --> 01:37:44.326
There you go.

01:37:45.193 --> 01:37:46.094
[SIGHS]

01:38:05.480 --> 01:38:07.115
HARLAN: And in that
journey of dying,

01:38:08.550 --> 01:38:09.918
you see many things.

01:38:12.087 --> 01:38:14.589
But all issues I had passed.

01:38:16.558 --> 01:38:18.927
Because I was to be a witness.

01:38:20.395 --> 01:38:21.529
A helper.

01:38:23.365 --> 01:38:25.133
And that's the thing, I think,

01:38:26.334 --> 01:38:27.936
is important about death,

01:38:29.471 --> 01:38:31.306
is the ability for us

01:38:31.339 --> 01:38:32.440
to be witnesses.

01:38:33.541 --> 01:38:36.511
Not only for our births
of coming in,

01:38:38.113 --> 01:38:38.846
but going out.

01:38:41.349 --> 01:38:42.517
And that's what we have here.

01:38:43.986 --> 01:38:46.021
We've lost our town.
It's gone.

01:38:48.456 --> 01:38:50.525
But maybe there's
a birth someplace else.

01:38:52.427 --> 01:38:53.528
Maybe there's a blessing

01:38:55.397 --> 01:38:56.431
from that experience.

01:38:58.333 --> 01:38:59.567
I'm no longer afraid of death,

01:39:01.069 --> 01:39:04.672
but it's a lesson
that's taken me
60 years to learn.

01:42:27.975 --> 01:42:30.178
[RADIO STATIC]

01:42:30.212 --> 01:42:31.746
RADIO ANNOUNCER: As you stroll
around Northfork,

01:42:32.847 --> 01:42:35.717
take your last walk
down the dirt road

01:42:35.750 --> 01:42:37.919
that leads to where
your house may have been,

01:42:37.952 --> 01:42:41.956
and look at the trees
that you once climbed.

01:42:41.989 --> 01:42:45.893
Smile, and remember
those trees for what
they will become,

01:42:47.629 --> 01:42:49.331
future snags
for fishing tackle.

01:42:50.832 --> 01:42:52.900
As you continue your walk,
think to yourself,

01:42:54.469 --> 01:42:58.373
"This is the only time
I will ever be able to walk

01:42:59.374 --> 01:43:00.275
"on the bottom of a lake

01:43:01.343 --> 01:43:02.644
"without having
to hold my breath."

01:43:04.111 --> 01:43:06.414
Remember when you leave
to pack all
your good memories.

01:43:07.915 --> 01:43:09.417
No one else will pack them
for you.

01:43:10.885 --> 01:43:11.953
Good night to you all.
